"Otto-Bliesner B.L., Upchurch Jr. G.R.","Vegetation-induced warming of high-latitude regions during the late Cretaceous period",1997,"Nature","385","6619",,"804","807",,,10.1038/385804a0,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0030621205&partnerID=40&md5=b40266ebdf15b3eabdf43cd977a19974","Climate Change Research, Natl. Ctr. for Atmospheric Research, Boulder, CO 80307-3000, United States; Department of Biology, Southwest Texas State University, San Marcos, TX 78666, United States","Otto-Bliesner, B.L., Climate Change Research, Natl. Ctr. for Atmospheric Research, Boulder, CO 80307-3000, United States; Upchurch Jr., G.R., Department of Biology, Southwest Texas State University, San Marcos, TX 78666, United States","Modelling studies of pre-Quaternary (>2 million years ago) climate implicate atmospheric carbon dioxide concentrations, land elevation and land- sea distribution as important factors influencing global climate change over geological timescales. But during times of global warmth, such as the Cretaceous period and Eocene epoch, there are large discrepancies between model simulations of high-latitude and continental-interior temperatures and those indicated by palaeotemperature records. Here we use a global climate model for the latest Cretaceous (66 million years ago) to examine the role played by high- and middle-latitude forests in surface temperature regulation. In our simulations, this forest vegetation warms the global climate by 2.2°C. The low- albedo deciduous forests cause high-latitude land areas to warm, which then transfer more heat to adjacent oceans, thus delaying sea-ice formation and increasing winter temperatures over coastal land. Overall, the inclusion of some of the physical and physiological climate feedback effects of high-latitude forest vegetation in our simulations reduces the existing discrepancies between observed and modelled climates of the latest Cretaceous, suggesting that these forests may have made an important contribution to climate regulation during periods of global warmth.",,"carbon dioxide; article; atmosphere; carbon dioxide tension; environmental temperature; forest; global climate; greenhouse effect; priority journal; sea; vegetation; warming; Cretaceous; forest; global warming; high latitude region; palaeoclimate",,,,,,"Barron, E.J., Fawcett, P.J., Pollard, D., Thompson, S., (1993) Phil. Trans. R. Soc. Lond. B, 341, pp. 307-315; Otto-Bliesner, B.L., (1993) Geophys. Res. Lett., 20, pp. 1947-1950; Barron, E.J., Washington, W.M., (1984) J. Geophys. Res., 89, pp. 1267-1279; Crowley, T.J., Short, D.A., Mengel, J.G., North, G.R., (1986) Science, 231, pp. 579-584; Otto-Bliesner, B.L., (1995) J. Geophys. Res., 100, pp. 11537-11548; Barron, E.J., Washington, W.M., (1982) Palaeogeogr. Palaeoclimatol. Palaeoecol., 40, pp. 103-133; Wing, S.L., Greenwood, D.R., (1993) Phil. Trans. R. Soc. Lond. B, 341, pp. 243-252; Thompson, S.L., Pollard, D., (1995) J. Clim., 8, pp. 732-761; Pollard, D., Thompson, S.L., (1995) Glob. Planet. Change, 10, pp. 129-161; Dorman, J.L., Sellers, P.J., (1989) J. Appl. Meteorol., 28, pp. 833-855; Berner, R.A., (1994) Am. J. Sci., 294, pp. 56-91; Andrews, J.E., Tandon, S.K., Dennis, D.F., (1995) J. Geol. Soc. Lond., 152, pp. 1-3; Scotese, C.R., Gahagan, L.M., Larson, R.L., (1988) Tectonophysics, 155, pp. 27-48; Ziegler, A.M., (1985) Annu. Rev. Earth Planet. Sci., 13, pp. 385-425; Hay, W.W., (1984) Proc. 27th Int. Geol. Congr., 6, pp. 15-38. , VNU Science Press, Amsterdam; Crowley, T.J., Baum, S.K., (1992) Geology, 20, pp. 507-510; Creber, G.T., Chaloner, W.G., (1985) Palaeogeogr. Palaeoclimatol. Palaeoecol., 52, pp. 35-60; Horrell, M.A., (1991) Palaeogeogr. Palaeoclimatol. Palaeoecol., 86, pp. 87-138; Wolfe, J.A., Upchurch Jr., G.R., (1987) Palaeogeogr. Palaeoclimatol. Palaeoecol., 61, pp. 33-77; Muller, J., (1981) Bot. Rev., 47, pp. 1-142; Crepet, W.L., Feldman, G.D., (1991) Am. J. Bot., 78, pp. 1010-1014; Köppen, W., (1936) Handbuch der Klimatologie, , (